column2: HOW DO I COMVERT GRAMS INTO MOLES
column5: You must first find the molar mass of the element or compound. Use the periodic table. If the chemical is an element#Comma just read off the atomic mass from the periodic table. If it is a compound#Comma you must know the molecular formula#Comma and then you find the total molar mass of the compound by adding up the atomic masses of each atom in the compound. The unit of the molar mass will be in grams per moles (g/mole). Once you have the molar mass#Comma you can easily convert from grams to moles#Comma and also from moles to grams. #Newline#NewlineNumber of moles = (# of grams) ÷ (molar mass)#NewlineNumber of grams = (# of moles) × (molar mass)#Newline#NewlineHere is an example: How many moles are in 5 grams of O2? #NewlineThe molar mass of O2 = 16.00 g/mole x 2 (for 2 atoms of oxygen) or 32.00 g/mole. #Newline5 grams of O2 ÷ (32 g/mole) = 0.15625 moles #Newline#Newline<think><set name="emotion">interested</set></think>
